Setting.Name: Low Pass Filter Signal Before Downsampling

Comment.Text: This scenario demonstrates how to do Event-Related Spectral Perturbation (ERSP) type visualization with OpenViBE.
A lua script is used to make an event timeline consisting of two types of trials, left and right, and the rest interpreted as... rest.
Set oscillation frequency dependending on the timeline (trial type or rest).

Dampen the signal within-trial in regular intervals to illustrate how the ERSP plot can evolve over time. Every other second will be dampened during the first 5s, controlled by the events from the timeline generator.
In the default configuration you should see the clear differences in the spectral powers over time in the conditions Left, Right and Rest. The last few seconds of each 5s are rest.
This side computes and displays the ERSP plot

We do two separate estimates: one for Left and another for Right. The signal is routed accordingly.
Stimulation based epoching is configured with the trial length.
Time based epoching further splits the trial to segments as desired.
Each segment gets its own spectral power computation.

This left hand side chain here generates a 1-channel signal that gets modulated differently depending on the trial type. The same processing could be used for multichannel signals.
The signal does not attempt to model real EEG, but to clearly illustrate the ERSP visualization.
You can browse each box' documentation by selecting the box and pressing F1

If the ERSP Average receives k consequent spectra for each trial t ( that is, a sequence s1(t),...,sk(t) ], the box computes their averages over t: result is a set of spectra s1,...,sk, where s1 = 1/n sum_t(s1(t)) and so on. These average spectra are then shown by the Stacked Bitmap.
The ERSP will be only visualized after all the data has been received.

Bury the clean signal in noise. If you change the number of trials in the Timeline Generator, you will notice that with only a few trials, the ERSP plot does not clearly show the spectral structure over time. With more trials, the noise gets averaged out.
